<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-064-630  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 064 630.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Feb 21 1989 v3 n8 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hard drive vendors slash prices in wake of Apple reductions.andO;(Apple Computer Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mathews, Renee.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   GCC Technologies Inc. (prices)Rodime Inc. (prices)Apple Computer Inc. (prices).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     DrivesPrice CuttingMarketing Strategy.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Hard drive vendors slash prices in wake of Apple reductionsandM;At least two third-party hard drive vendors are cutting prices and others arere-evaluating their markeitng strategies in the aftermath of Apple's pricecuts on its storage devices.andM;In January, Apple cuts suggested retail prices of its 20-, 40- and 80-Mbyteinternal and external hard drives by 18 percent to 25 percent.andM;Last week GCC Technologies of Waltham, Mass., followed Apple's lead, reducingits drive prices by s much as 22 percent.andP;  Rodime Inc. of Boca Raton, Fla.,andO;recently cut its retail prices by 18 percent to 36 percent.andM;&quot;Apple is trying to sell more disk drives and DRAM at the expense of others,&quot;said Tim Mahoney, Rodime's vice president of marketing and sales.andP;  Rodime'sintent is to offer more aggressive pricing on higher-capacity drives, Mahoneyadded.andP;  &quot;We're beating Apple's price by offering a 70-Mbyte drive at the sameprice as Apple's 40-Mbyte drive,&quot; he said.andM;Larry Concannon, mass storage product manager at GCC, said price cuts ondrive products by Apple and other manufacturers will have a negative effecton dealers.andP;  &quot;For a period of time, dealers were able to put together theirown packages with Apple CPU's and third-party drives.andP;  They made more ontheir margins and were able to offer their customers lower prices than ifthey bought Apple-only [products],&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;Now all of a sudden Applewants that business back, and it's taking it back through [reduce] pricing.&quot;andM;But according to industry observers, declining drive prices in the Mac marketare simply an evolutionary process.andP;  &quot;The amount end users have had to payfor a hard drive for the Mac is rather scandalous compared with drives withthe same capacity and performance for IBM or IBM-compatible machines,&quot; notedJim Porter, president of Disk/Trend Inc., a Mountain View, Calif., researchcompany.andP;  He said while Apple's price cuts will cut a few pennies fromreseller margins, the move will benefit end users by increasing competitionand driving down market prices, as was the case in the IBM drive market.andM;Greg Brashier, product marketing manager at Storage Dimensions in San Jose,Calif., expects that the new pricing may run many disk drive vendors out ofthe Mac market entirely or cause them to switch to another product line.andO;&quot;The days of the garage-shop disk drive startups are definitely over for awhile,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;But overall [the prices cuts] will probably clear up a lotof channel problems.&quot;andM;While third-party vendors may have trouble beating Apple's pricing on harddrives bundled with CPU's they will continue to dominate the high-capacitysegment, several drie makers said.andP;  Apple's largest drive to date offers only80 Mbytes, although a model with twice that capacity is expected soon.andO;</TEXT></DOC>